      "- **Execute on-site.** A detailed run-of-show, a full tech rehearsal, and a calm production team.",
      "- **Report and follow up.** Measure results against the original objective and capture lessons for next time.",
      "[TIP] The single biggest predictor of a smooth event in Saudi Arabia is **lead time**. The earlier you lock your venue and start your GEA permit, the more options and leverage you have — and the less you pay in rush fees.",
      "## How Much Does Event Planning Cost in Saudi Arabia?",
      "This is the question everyone asks first, and the honest answer is: it depends enormously on type, scale, city, and ambition. A modest corporate seminar and a royal wedding are not in the same universe. That said, transparency matters, so here are realistic 2026 ranges based on full-service, professionally produced events. These figures cover venue, production, catering, décor, and management for a mid-to-premium event.",
      "| Event Type | Typical Guest Count | Realistic 2026 Budget Range (SAR) |",
      "| :--- | :--- | :--- |",
      "| **Corporate conference / seminar** | 150–500 | 250,000 – 1,200,000 |",
      "| **Corporate gala / awards night** | 300–800 | 600,000 – 3,000,000 |",
      "| **Exhibition / trade show** | 2,000–20,000+ | 1,500,000 – 15,000,000+ |",
      "| **Luxury wedding (Riyadh/Jeddah)** | 300–600 | 1,500,000 – 5,000,000+ |",
      "| **Destination wedding (AlUla/Red Sea)** | 100–200 | 2,500,000 – 8,000,000+ |",
      "| **VIP / private gathering** | 50–200 | 300,000 – 2,000,000+ |",
      "These ranges are wide on purpose — a gala in a five-star ballroom with a regional headline performer sits at the top, while a polished but restrained corporate dinner sits near the bottom. Three factors move you up the scale fastest: **custom production** (LED, scenic builds, projection mapping), **premium catering** (SAR 1,200–3,500+ per head at the luxury end), and **remote logistics** (an AlUla or NEOM location adds roughly 40–60% versus the same event in Riyadh).",
      "[INSIGHT] As a rule of thumb for premium corporate events, expect venue to consume 25–35% of budget, food and beverage 20–30%, production and AV 15–25%, and décor 10–20% — with the remainder going to talent, staffing, permits, and contingency.",
      "Where can you save without looking cheap? Spend on the things guests actually experience — lighting, sound, food, and the welcome — and economise on the things they never notice. A skilled planner earns their fee many times over by knowing exactly where that line sits.",
