      "[TIP] Match the city to the message. A futuristic tech launch feels right in Riyadh or NEOM; a romantic wedding belongs in Jeddah or AlUla; an energy-sector summit makes sense in Dammam. The setting should reinforce your story, not fight it.",
      "## How to Choose the Right Event Management Company",
      "Your choice of partner matters more than any other decision you will make. A great [event management company](/services/corporate-events) protects your budget, navigates permits, and turns your vision into reality — while a weak one creates expensive, stressful chaos. Use this checklist when you evaluate firms:",
      "- **Relevant portfolio.** Have they delivered events like yours — same scale, same city, same category — and can they prove it?",
      "- **Local expertise.** Do they genuinely understand GEA permits, RCU approvals, municipality rules, and Saudi cultural protocol?",
      "- **Vendor network.** Do they have established, preferred relationships with top venues and suppliers (which means better rates and priority access)?",
      "- **Production capability.** Can they handle serious AV, staging, and lighting in-house or through trusted partners?",
      "- **VIP and protocol experience.** Have they managed royal, government, or high-net-worth guests with the required discretion?",
      "- **Budget transparency.** Do they give you itemised, honest costings — or vague lump sums that hide their margin?",
      "- **Communication.** Are they responsive, organised, and calm under pressure during the proposal stage? That is how they will be on event day.",
      "[MISTAKE] Choosing a planner on price alone. The cheapest quote almost always means cut corners, weaker vendors, or hidden costs that surface later. Judge value, track record, and trust — not just the bottom line.",
